{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1780728371635,"sessionID":"ses_164517a7bffeIaaPynAQONhoL2","part":{"id":"prt_e9bae99b1001Q4Aso5PsTBdtmz","messageID":"msg_e9bae8aca0016US3GawQg7j66u","sessionID":"ses_164517a7bffeIaaPynAQONhoL2","snapshot":"de4284b9f18d405cd680dc243dbda65e719c1b39","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1780728389999,"sessionID":"ses_164517a7bffeIaaPynAQONhoL2","part":{"id":"prt_e9baeb973001zCrO13uSjfIYXp","messageID":"msg_e9bae8aca0016US3GawQg7j66u","sessionID":"ses_164517a7bffeIaaPynAQONhoL2","type":"text","text":"I’ll inspect the specified MemClaw entry points and nearby tool implementation files read-only, then synthesize only the requested governance comparison with file:line citations.","time":{"start":1780728379763,"end":1780728389998},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_06a9a7f5e5b14fe9016a23c23bbd4881919fe9682da224bdb4","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780728390050,"sessionID":"ses_164517a7bffeIaaPynAQONhoL2","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_focmVoQICqkjTAMt27L3fM7o","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/docs/api-surfaces.md","offset":1,"limit":220},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/docs/api-surfaces.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # API Surface Ownership Charter\n2: \n3: MemClaw exposes three callable surfaces — REST, MCP, and the OpenClaw plugin.\n4: They are intentionally **not symmetric**. Each serves a different audience and\n5: operates under different assumptions. This document records who owns what and\n6: when to add or move an operation.\n7: \n8: > Looking for **latency and throughput numbers** per surface? See\n9: > [`performance.md`](performance.md). This document is about *which surface\n10: > owns which operation*, not about how fast each one runs.\n11: \n12: ## Audiences\n13: \n14: | Surface | Primary audience | Trust model |\n15: |---------|------------------|-------------|\n16: | REST    | Web UI, ops dashboards, programmatic admins, scripted clients | Explicit `tenant_id` in body/query; API key + role gating; full operational vocabulary. |\n17: | MCP     | AI agents (Claude Code, third-party agents) | Tenant inferred from auth header; agent-natural operations; description-driven discoverability. |\n18: | OpenClaw plugin | Local plugin runtime that hosts agents | Operational concerns of the local install — heartbeat, agent registration, fleet readiness. Delegates business operations to MCP. |\n19: \n20: ## Surface ownership\n21: \n22: | Concern | Owner | Reason |\n23: |---------|-------|--------|\n24: | Memory CRUD (write/recall/list/get/update/delete/transition) | REST + MCP | Universal; needed by every audience. |\n25: | Bulk write | REST + MCP | Same. |\n26: | Per-agent search profile (tune) | REST + MCP | Both administrators (REST) and agents tuning themselves (MCP) need it. |\n27: | Doc CRUD | REST + MCP | Universal. |\n28: | Doc semantic search | MCP **and** REST | Was MCP-only; REST endpoint added so non-MCP clients can use vector search on documents. |\n29: | Doc list-collections | MCP **and** REST | Was MCP-only; REST endpoint added for parity with list use cases. |\n30: | Bulk delete | REST + MCP (`memclaw_manage op=bulk_delete`) | Admin sometimes; agents cleaning up after themselves sometimes. |\n31: | Memory lineage walk | REST + MCP (`memclaw_manage op=lineage`) | Agents reviewing their own writes need to trace supersession chains. |\n32: | Knowledge graph / `/graph` | REST only | Aggregation surface for UIs and analytics tools. Agents that need entity context use `memclaw_entity_get` (single entity) and `memclaw_recall` (with entity_links in results). |\n33: | Memory stats | REST + MCP (`memclaw_stats`) | Aggregate counts (total + breakdown by type, agent, status; opt-in `include_deleted=true` adds `deleted` and `total_including_deleted`) — useful for admin/dashboard usage on REST and for agent self-introspection on MCP. Read-only aggregations don't need a use-case gate. |\n34: | Skill sharing | REST (`/documents` + `/documents/search` on `collection=\"skills\"`) + MCP (`memclaw_doc op=write\\|read\\|query\\|delete\\|search collection=skills`) | Skill sharing rides the generic document surface. Slugs (`doc_id`) are constrained to `^[a-z0-9][a-z0-9._-]{0,99}$` (filesystem-safe), and skills writes require `data[\"summary\"]` (with back-compat fallback to `data[\"description\"]`) so the catalog is semantic-searchable without ceremony. The dedicated `memclaw_share_skill`/`memclaw_unshare_skill` tools and `/skills/*` REST routes were dropped 2026-05; fleet auto-install (push to every node) is restored by Phase A's plugin-side reconciler. Trust ≥ 1 (inherited from `memclaw_doc`). |\n35: | Keystones (mandatory rules) | REST (`/memclaw/keystones`) + MCP (`memclaw_keystones` read, `memclaw_keystones_set` set\\|delete) | Governance policies that agents MUST obey — fetched deterministically (no semantic search) and injected into every session by the OpenClaw plugin. Storage lives in the system-managed `_keystones` collection on `documents`; the dedicated surface exists so the read tool stays discoverable in MCP `instructions` and the write surface can be trust-gated separately. Reads are open. Writes are tiered: a freshly-registered (trust ≥ 1) agent can author its own `scope=agent` rule — self-authored autonomy — but `scope=fleet`, `scope=tenant`, and cross-agent `scope=agent` stay at trust ≥ 2 so a default-trust agent (or a prompt-injected one) can't plant a tenant-wide rule. |\n36: | Tenant settings | REST only | Settings are a tenant-administrator concern; not safe for arbitrary agents to flip global config. |\n37: | Redistribute (mass reassign) | REST only | Destructive bulk op requires `trust_level >= 3`. Admin operation, not agent-driven. |\n38: | Ingest preview/commit | REST only (revisit per use case) | Pipeline workflow; expose to MCP only if \"agent crawls a URL and writes memories\" becomes a real use case. |\n39: | Contradictions / lineage at `/memories/{id}/contradictions` | REST + MCP (`memclaw_manage op=lineage`) | UI gets the rich endpoint; agents get the focused tool. |\n40: | Heartbeat / fleet readiness | REST receives, plugin produces | Plugin is the natural producer (it knows the local node state). REST is the receiver. MCP doesn't need this — agents don't report their own runtime state. |\n41: | Agent registration | OpenClaw plugin | Local-runtime concern. |\n42: \n43: ## When to add an operation\n44: \n45: Before adding a new MCP tool that mirrors a REST endpoint, justify it with a\n46: concrete agent workflow OR demonstrate that the operation is a read-only\n47: aggregation/introspection:\n48: \n49: 1. **Read-only aggregations** (counts, summaries, listings of caller-visible\n50:    state) don't need a blocking use case — they're cheap, safe, and useful for\n51:    any agent that wants to introspect the store. Add freely; trust gate at\n52:    the same level as `memclaw_list` (≥ 1 for own scope, ≥ 2 for cross-agent).\n53: 2. For everything else: is there an agent that **today** is blocked from\n54:    doing useful work because this operation only exists on REST?\n55: 3. If yes, does it fit naturally into an existing tool (`memclaw_manage`,\n56:    `memclaw_doc`, etc.) as another `op=...`? Prefer extending an existing\n57:    tool over adding a new top-level surface.\n58: 4. If a new tool is genuinely warranted, it must include: a clear description,\n59:    trust-level enforcement consistent with the REST counterpart, and a wet\n60:    test that exercises the same workflow against the local docker stack.\n61: \n62: Before adding a new REST endpoint that mirrors an MCP tool, justify it with a\n63: concrete non-agent workflow (a UI screen, a script, an integration). Don't\n64: mirror \"for symmetry.\"\n65: \n66: ## What this charter is NOT\n67: \n68: - It's not a list of bugs. Asymmetry is the design, not a defect.\n69: - It's not exhaustive — new operations should be classified above when added.\n70: - It's not a justification for current cross-surface drift in error contracts\n71:   or response shapes — those are separate hygiene concerns and should be\n72:   fixed regardless of where each operation lives.\n73: \n74: ## Cross-surface hygiene (separate from ownership)\n75: \n76: The following inconsistencies span surfaces and should be addressed\n77: independently of ownership decisions:\n78: \n79: - **Error contracts**: REST raises `HTTPException` with status codes; MCP\n80:   returns string error prefixes (`\"Error (422): ...\"`). Cross-surface clients\n81:   must special-case. Pick one canonical shape and align both surfaces.\n82: - **Response shape drift on `recall`**: REST `/recall` returns\n83:   `{query, summary, memory_count, memories, recall_ms}`; MCP\n84:   `memclaw_recall(include_brief=true)` returns\n85:   `{results, brief: <REST-recall-response>}`. Same conceptual operation,\n86:   different payloads. Pick one and align.\n87: - **Tenant resolution**: REST takes `body.tenant_id`; MCP infers from auth\n88:   header. Both are reasonable; document the convention.\n\n(End of file - total 88 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# API Surface Ownership Charter\n\nMemClaw exposes three callable surfaces — REST, MCP, and the OpenClaw plugin.\nThey are intentionally **not symmetric**. Each serves a different audience and\noperates under different assumptions. This document records who owns what and\nwhen to add or move an operation.\n\n> Looking for **latency and throughput numbers** per surface? See\n> [`performance.md`](performance.md). This document is about *which surface\n> owns which operation*, not about how fast each one runs.\n\n## Audiences\n\n| Surface | Primary audience | Trust model |\n|---------|------------------|-------------|\n| REST    | Web UI, ops dashboards, programmatic admins, scripted clients | Explicit `tenant_id` in body/query; API key + role gating; full operational vocabulary. |\n| MCP     | AI agents (Claude Code, third-party agents) | Tenant inferred from auth header; agent-natural operations; description-driven discoverability. |\n| OpenClaw plugin | Local plugin runtime that hosts agents | Operational concerns of the local install — heartbeat, agent registration, fleet readiness. Delegates business operations to MCP. |\n\n## Surface ownership","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/docs/api-surfaces.md","text":"# API Surface Ownership Charter\n\nMemClaw exposes three callable surfaces — REST, MCP, and the OpenClaw plugin.\nThey are intentionally **not symmetric**. Each serves a different audience and\noperates under different assumptions. This document records who owns what and\nwhen to add or move an operation.\n\n> Looking for **latency and throughput numbers** per surface? See\n> [`performance.md`](performance.md). This document is about *which surface\n> owns which operation*, not about how fast each one runs.\n\n## Audiences\n\n| Surface | Primary audience | Trust model |\n|---------|------------------|-------------|\n| REST    | Web UI, ops dashboards, programmatic admins, scripted clients | Explicit `tenant_id` in body/query; API key + role gating; full operational vocabulary. |\n| MCP     | AI agents (Claude Code, third-party agents) | Tenant inferred from auth header; agent-natural operations; description-driven discoverability. |\n| OpenClaw plugin | Local plugin runtime that hosts agents | Operational concerns of the local install — heartbeat, agent registration, fleet readiness. Delegates business operations to MCP. |\n\n## Surface ownership\n\n| Concern | Owner | Reason |\n|---------|-------|--------|\n| Memory CRUD (write/recall/list/get/update/delete/transition) | REST + MCP | Universal; needed by every audience. |\n| Bulk write | REST + MCP | Same. |\n| Per-agent search profile (tune) | REST + MCP | Both administrators (REST) and agents tuning themselves (MCP) need it. |\n| Doc CRUD | REST + MCP | Universal. |\n| Doc semantic search | MCP **and** REST | Was MCP-only; REST endpoint added so non-MCP clients can use vector search on documents. |\n| Doc list-collections | MCP **and** REST | Was MCP-only; REST endpoint added for parity with list use cases. |\n| Bulk delete | REST + MCP (`memclaw_manage op=bulk_delete`) | Admin sometimes; agents cleaning up after themselves sometimes. |\n| Memory lineage walk | REST + MCP (`memclaw_manage op=lineage`) | Agents reviewing their own writes need to trace supersession chains. |\n| Knowledge graph / `/graph` | REST only | Aggregation surface for UIs and analytics tools. Agents that need entity context use `memclaw_entity_get` (single entity) and `memclaw_recall` (with entity_links in results). |\n| Memory stats | REST + MCP (`memclaw_stats`) | Aggregate counts (total + breakdown by type, agent, status; opt-in `include_deleted=true` adds `deleted` and `total_including_deleted`) — useful for admin/dashboard usage on REST and for agent self-introspection on MCP. Read-only aggregations don't need a use-case gate. |\n| Skill sharing | REST (`/documents` + `/documents/search` on `collection=\"skills\"`) + MCP (`memclaw_doc op=write\\|read\\|query\\|delete\\|search collection=skills`) | Skill sharing rides the generic document surface. Slugs (`doc_id`) are constrained to `^[a-z0-9][a-z0-9._-]{0,99}$` (filesystem-safe), and skills writes require `data[\"summary\"]` (with back-compat fallback to `data[\"description\"]`) so the catalog is semantic-searchable without ceremony. The dedicated `memclaw_share_skill`/`memclaw_unshare_skill` tools and `/skills/*` REST routes were dropped 2026-05; fleet auto-install (push to every node) is restored by Phase A's plugin-side reconciler. Trust ≥ 1 (inherited from `memclaw_doc`). |\n| Keystones (mandatory rules) | REST (`/memclaw/keystones`) + MCP (`memclaw_keystones` read, `memclaw_keystones_set` set\\|delete) | Governance policies that agents MUST obey — fetched deterministically (no semantic search) and injected into every session by the OpenClaw plugin. Storage lives in the system-managed `_keystones` collection on `documents`; the dedicated surface exists so the read tool stays discoverable in MCP `instructions` and the write surface can be trust-gated separately. Reads are open. Writes are tiered: a freshly-registered (trust ≥ 1) agent can author its own `scope=agent` rule — self-authored autonomy — but `scope=fleet`, `scope=tenant`, and cross-agent `scope=agent` stay at trust ≥ 2 so a default-trust agent (or a prompt-injected one) can't plant a tenant-wide rule. |\n| Tenant settings | REST only | Settings are a tenant-administrator concern; not safe for arbitrary agents to flip global config. |\n| Redistribute (mass reassign) | REST only | Destructive bulk op requires `trust_level >= 3`. Admin operation, not agent-driven. |\n| Ingest preview/commit | REST only (revisit per use case) | Pipeline workflow; expose to MCP only if \"agent crawls a URL and writes memories\" becomes a real use case. |\n| Contradictions / lineage at `/memories/{id}/contradictions` | REST + MCP (`memclaw_manage op=lineage`) | UI gets the rich endpoint; agents get the focused tool. |\n| Heartbeat / fleet readiness | REST receives, plugin produces | Plugin is the natural producer (it knows the local node state). REST is the receiver. MCP doesn't need this — agents don't report their own runtime state. |\n| Agent registration | OpenClaw plugin | Local-runtime concern. |\n\n## When to add an operation\n\nBefore adding a new MCP tool that mirrors a REST endpoint, justify it with a\nconcrete agent workflow OR demonstrate that the operation is a read-only\naggregation/introspection:\n\n1. **Read-only aggregations** (counts, summaries, listings of caller-visible\n   state) don't need a blocking use case — they're cheap, safe, and useful for\n   any agent that wants to introspect the store. Add freely; trust gate at\n   the same level as `memclaw_list` (≥ 1 for own scope, ≥ 2 for cross-agent).\n2. For everything else: is there an agent that **today** is blocked from\n   doing useful work because this operation only exists on REST?\n3. If yes, does it fit naturally into an existing tool (`memclaw_manage`,\n   `memclaw_doc`, etc.) as another `op=...`? Prefer extending an existing\n   tool over adding a new top-level surface.\n4. If a new tool is genuinely warranted, it must include: a clear description,\n   trust-level enforcement consistent with the REST counterpart, and a wet\n   test that exercises the same workflow against the local docker stack.\n\nBefore adding a new REST endpoint that mirrors an MCP tool, justify it with a\nconcrete non-agent workflow (a UI screen, a script, an integration). Don't\nmirror \"for symmetry.\"\n\n## What this charter is NOT\n\n- It's not a list of bugs. Asymmetry is the design, not a defect.\n- It's not exhaustive — new operations should be classified above when added.\n- It's not a justification for current cross-surface drift in error contracts\n  or response shapes — those are separate hygiene concerns and should be\n  fixed regardless of where each operation lives.\n\n## Cross-surface hygiene (separate from ownership)\n\nThe following inconsistencies span surfaces and should be addressed\nindependently of ownership decisions:\n\n- **Error contracts**: REST raises `HTTPException` with status codes; MCP\n  returns string error prefixes (`\"Error (422): ...\"`). Cross-surface clients\n  must special-case. Pick one canonical shape and align both surfaces.\n- **Response shape drift on `recall`**: REST `/recall` returns\n  `{query, summary, memory_count, memories, recall_ms}`; MCP\n  `memclaw_recall(include_brief=true)` returns\n  `{results, brief: <REST-recall-response>}`. Same conceptual operation,\n  different payloads. Pick one and align.\n- **Tenant resolution**: REST takes `body.tenant_id`; MCP infers from auth\n  header. Both are reasonable; document the convention.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":88,"totalLines":88,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/docs/api-surfaces.md","time":{"start":1780728390036,"end":1780728390047}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_06a9a7f5e5b14fe9016a23c245ec1081918da66463fe829f0e"}},"id":"prt_e9baee171001Mhb2EqY0cCpXIa","sessionID":"ses_164517a7bffeIaaPynAQONhoL2","messageID":"msg_e9bae8aca0016US3GawQg7j66u"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780728390072,"sessionID":"ses_164517a7bffeIaaPynAQONhoL2","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_e6erxJbxz5hsCZi4XbWbizyx","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py","offset":1,"limit":260},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: \"\"\"MCP (Model Context Protocol) server for MemClaw.\n2: \n3: Exposes MemClaw tools over Streamable HTTP so any MCP client\n4: (Claude Desktop, Claude Code, Cursor, etc.) can connect with just a URL + API key.\n5: \n6: Mounted onto the main FastAPI app at /mcp.\n7: \"\"\"\n8: \n9: import contextlib\n10: import contextvars\n11: import hmac as _hmac\n12: import json\n13: import logging\n14: import re\n15: import time\n16: from typing import Annotated, cast\n17: from uuid import UUID, uuid4\n18: \n19: import httpx\n20: from fastapi import HTTPException\n21: from mcp.server.fastmcp import FastMCP\n22: from mcp.server.transport_security import TransportSecuritySettings\n23: from mcp.types import CallToolResult, TextContent\n24: from pydantic import Field, ValidationError\n25: from sqlalchemy import text as sa_text\n26: from starlette.types import ASGIApp, Receive, Scope, Send\n27: \n28: from common.enrichment.constants import SERVER_RESERVED_MEMORY_TYPES\n29: from core_api.auth import get_admin_key\n30: from core_api.clients.storage_client import KeystoneUpsertPayload, get_storage_client\n31: from core_api.constants import (\n32:     DEFAULT_SEARCH_TOP_K,\n33:     EVOLVE_OUTCOME_TYPES,\n34:     INSIGHTS_FOCUS_MODES,\n35:     MAX_SEARCH_TOP_K,\n36:     MEMORY_STATUSES,\n37:     MEMORY_TYPES,\n38:     VALID_SCOPES,\n39:     VERSION,\n40: )\n41: from core_api.db.session import async_session\n42: from core_api.errors import code_for_status\n43: from core_api.repositories import memory_repo\n44: from core_api.schemas import BulkMemoryCreate, BulkMemoryItem, MemoryCreate, MemoryUpdate\n45: from core_api.services.agent_service import (\n46:     authorize_memory_access,\n47:     enforce_delete,\n48:     enforce_fleet_read,\n49:     enforce_fleet_write,\n50: )\n51: from core_api.services.audit_service import log_action, log_cross_tenant_read\n52: from core_api.services.entity_service import get_entity\n53: from core_api.services.memory_service import (\n54:     create_memories_bulk,\n55:     create_memory,\n56:     search_memories,\n57:     soft_delete_memory,\n58:     update_memory,\n59: )\n60: \n61: # Re-export so existing `monkeypatch.setattr(mcp_server, \"_require_trust\", ...)`\n62: # sites in tests keep working; production callers should import ``require_trust``\n63: # directly from ``core_api.services.trust_service``.\n64: from core_api.services.trust_service import parse_trust_error\n65: from core_api.services.trust_service import require_trust as _require_trust\n66: from core_api.services.usage_service import check_and_increment_by_tenant as check_and_increment\n67: from core_api.trust_utils import effective_keystone_min_trust, keystone_min_trust\n68: \n69: logger = logging.getLogger(__name__)\n70: \n71: # ── Auth via context vars ──\n72: \n73: _tenant_id_var: contextvars.ContextVar[str] = contextvars.ContextVar(\"mcp_tenant_id\")\n74: _agent_id_var: contextvars.ContextVar[str | None] = contextvars.ContextVar(\"mcp_agent_id\", default=None)\n75: # True iff X-Tenant-ID arrived as a request header (gateway-routed). On that\n76: # path the gateway is the source of truth for identity; falling back to the\n77: # literal \"mcp-agent\" tool-param default would silently attribute every write\n78: # from a tenant-key holder to a single shared identity (friction §2.8 / Stage 6b).\n79: _via_gateway_var: contextvars.ContextVar[bool] = contextvars.ContextVar(\"mcp_via_gateway\", default=False)\n80: # Cross-tenant read set plumbed from X-Readable-Tenant-IDs (CSV). Empty list\n81: # means single-tenant key (reads pinned to ``_tenant_id_var``). When populated\n82: # the home tenant_id is the first element and writes still go there.\n83: _readable_tenant_ids_var: contextvars.ContextVar[list[str] | None] = contextvars.ContextVar(\n84:     \"mcp_readable_tenant_ids\", default=None\n85: )\n86: _scopes_var: contextvars.ContextVar[set[str] | None] = contextvars.ContextVar(\"mcp_scopes\", default=None)\n87: \n88: _UNAUTH = \"__unauthenticated__\"\n89: _ADMIN = \"__admin__\"\n90: _NO_AUTH = \"__no_auth__\"\n91: _DEFAULT_AGENT_ID = \"mcp-agent\"\n92: \n93: \n94: def _error_response(code: str, message: str, **details) -> str:\n95:     \"\"\"Return the canonical MCP error envelope as a JSON string.\n96: \n97:     Shape matches the REST surface (see ``core_api.errors.make_error_payload``):\n98:     ``{\"error\": {\"code\": \"...\", \"message\": \"...\", \"details\": {...}}}``.\n99: \n100:     The string is wrapped into a ``CallToolResult(isError=True)`` before\n101:     leaving the tool — either by ``_with_latency`` (which detects the\n102:     error shape) or by ``_as_error_result`` for pre-tool returns that\n103:     skip the latency stamp. Tool callsites keep returning plain strings;\n104:     the wrap happens at one of those two chokepoints (CAURA-000,\n105:     FRICTION-REPORT-V3 B2 — clients literal-reading the MCP spec were\n106:     seeing ``isError=False`` on every gateway-side refusal).\n107:     \"\"\"\n108:     from core_api.errors import make_error_payload\n109: \n110:     payload = make_error_payload(code, message, details=details if details else None)\n111:     return json.dumps(payload, default=str)\n112: \n113: \n114: def _as_error_result(envelope: str) -> CallToolResult:\n115:     \"\"\"Wrap a ``_error_response`` JSON envelope into a CallToolResult\n116:     with ``isError=True``. The envelope JSON is preserved verbatim in\n117:     a single TextContent so callers reading ``result.content[0].text``\n118:     still get the structured payload. Used for the pre-tool / auth\n119:     return paths that don't run through ``_with_latency``.\n120:     \"\"\"\n121:     return CallToolResult(\n122:         content=[TextContent(type=\"text\", text=envelope)],\n123:         isError=True,\n124:     )\n125: \n126: \n127: # Pre-tool auth errors (returned directly, NOT through _with_latency, because\n128: # they fire before any tool work has begun, so we wrap them as\n129: # CallToolResults at module load — every tool that returns one\n130: # propagates ``isError=True`` to the MCP client.\n131: _AUTH_ERROR = _as_error_result(\n132:     _error_response(\n133:         \"UNAUTHORIZED\",\n134:         \"Missing or invalid X-API-Key header. Provide a tenant-scoped API key.\",\n135:     )\n136: )\n137: _ADMIN_ERROR = _as_error_result(\n138:     _error_response(\n139:         \"FORBIDDEN\",\n140:         \"Admin/system keys cannot be used with MCP. Use a tenant-scoped API key.\",\n141:     )\n142: )\n143: \n144: \n145: class MCPAuthMiddleware:\n146:     \"\"\"ASGI middleware that resolves X-API-Key to tenant_id before MCP handlers run.\"\"\"\n147: \n148:     def __init__(self, app: ASGIApp):\n149:         self.app = app\n150: \n151:     async def __call__(self, scope: Scope, receive: Receive, send: Send):\n152:         if scope[\"type\"] == \"http\":\n153:             from core_api.config import settings\n154: \n155:             headers = dict(scope.get(\"headers\", []))\n156: \n157:             # Preferred path: enterprise nginx has already validated the\n158:             # session cookie / JWT / API key via auth_request and injected\n159:             # X-Tenant-ID. Trust that resolution verbatim — otherwise a\n160:             # browser dashboard call (which sends `Authorization: Bearer\n161:             # <session JWT>` alongside the gateway-injected X-Tenant-ID)\n162:             # falls into the Authorization→api_key fallback below, fails\n163:             # the admin-key comparison, and reports UNAUTH despite the\n164:             # gateway having already approved the caller.\n165:             tenant_header = headers.get(b\"x-tenant-id\", b\"\").decode()\n166:             if tenant_header:\n167:                 _tenant_id_var.set(tenant_header)\n168:                 _via_gateway_var.set(True)\n169:             else:\n170:                 _via_gateway_var.set(False)\n171:                 api_key = headers.get(b\"x-api-key\", b\"\").decode()\n172:                 if not api_key:\n173:                     auth_header = headers.get(b\"authorization\", b\"\").decode()\n174:                     if auth_header.lower().startswith(\"bearer \"):\n175:                         api_key = auth_header[7:]\n176:                 admin_key = get_admin_key()\n177: \n178:                 if admin_key and api_key and _hmac.compare_digest(api_key, admin_key):\n179:                     _tenant_id_var.set(_ADMIN)\n180:                 elif settings.is_standalone:\n181:                     from core_api.standalone import get_standalone_tenant_id\n182: \n183:                     _tenant_id_var.set(get_standalone_tenant_id())\n184:                 elif not api_key:\n185:                     _tenant_id_var.set(_UNAUTH if admin_key else _NO_AUTH)\n186:                 else:\n187:                     _tenant_id_var.set(_UNAUTH)\n188: \n189:             # X-Agent-ID injected by enterprise gateway for agent-scoped\n190:             # credentials (kind=agent_key). When present, this is the\n191:             # cryptographically verified agent identity.\n192:             agent_header = headers.get(b\"x-agent-id\", b\"\").decode()\n193:             _agent_id_var.set(agent_header or None)\n194: \n195:             # X-Readable-Tenant-IDs and X-Key-Scopes are plumbed by the gateway\n196:             # for credentials authorized to read beyond their home tenant\n197:             # (cross-tenant agent keys). Absent / empty headers leave the\n198:             # context vars at their single-tenant defaults.\n199:             # Always reset both context vars at the start of every request,\n200:             # not just when the header is present. ContextVars set inside a\n201:             # prior request can survive into the next request when the\n202:             # underlying ASGI task is reused or the var was never assigned a\n203:             # token-based reset. An absent header means \"single-tenant /\n204:             # full-scope\" — make that explicit so a previous request's\n205:             # cross-tenant read-set or read-only scope cannot bleed through.\n206:             readable_header = headers.get(b\"x-readable-tenant-ids\", b\"\").decode()\n207:             _readable_tenant_ids_var.set(\n208:                 [t.strip() for t in readable_header.split(\",\") if t.strip()] if readable_header else None\n209:             )\n210:             # X-Capabilities is canonical from the unified auth-api;\n211:             # X-Key-Scopes is accepted as a back-compat alias during\n212:             # the gateway rollout window.\n213:             caps_header = (\n214:                 headers.get(b\"x-capabilities\", b\"\").decode() or headers.get(b\"x-key-scopes\", b\"\").decode()\n215:             )\n216:             _scopes_var.set({s.strip() for s in caps_header.split(\",\") if s.strip()} if caps_header else None)\n217: \n218:         await self.app(scope, receive, send)\n219: \n220: \n221: def _get_tenant() -> str:\n222:     return _tenant_id_var.get(_UNAUTH)\n223: \n224: \n225: def _get_agent_id() -> str | None:\n226:     \"\"\"Return the verified agent_id from X-Agent-ID header, or None.\"\"\"\n227:     return _agent_id_var.get(None)\n228: \n229: \n230: def _get_readable_tenants() -> list[str]:\n231:     \"\"\"Return the cross-tenant read set; empty for single-tenant keys.\"\"\"\n232:     return _readable_tenant_ids_var.get(None) or []\n233: \n234: \n235: def _get_scopes() -> set[str] | None:\n236:     \"\"\"Return the credential's scope set, or None for full-scope (legacy) keys.\"\"\"\n237:     return _scopes_var.get(None)\n238: \n239: \n240: def _is_write_allowed() -> bool:\n241:     \"\"\"Return False if the active credential is scope-limited to read-only.\"\"\"\n242:     scopes = _get_scopes()\n243:     if scopes is None:\n244:         return True\n245:     return \"write\" in scopes\n246: \n247: \n248: def _refuse_default_agent_on_gateway(agent_id: str) -> str | None:\n249:     \"\"\"When the request came through the enterprise gateway (X-Tenant-ID set)\n250:     and the gateway didn't inject X-Agent-ID (mc_ tenant-key path), the caller\n251:     must supply a real agent_id. Falling back to the reserved ``\"mcp-agent\"``\n252:     default would silently attribute every write from a tenant-key holder to\n253:     one shared identity — the failure mode the friction report's bug repro\n254:     documented as ``agent row missing from list_agents``.\n255: \n256:     Returns an error envelope if the call should be refused; ``None`` to proceed.\n257:     Standalone, admin, and gateway-routed agent-scoped paths are unaffected:\n258:     standalone uses a stable single-tenant identity, admin is a system caller,\n259:     and an agent-scoped credential resolves X-Agent-ID via auth_validate so\n260:     this guard never fires for it.\n\n(Showing lines 1-260 of 2542. Use offset=261 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"\"\"\"MCP (Model Context Protocol) server for MemClaw.\n\nExposes MemClaw tools over Streamable HTTP so any MCP client\n(Claude Desktop, Claude Code, Cursor, etc.) can connect with just a URL + API key.\n\nMounted onto the main FastAPI app at /mcp.\n\"\"\"\n\nimport contextlib\nimport contextvars\nimport hmac as _hmac\nimport json\nimport logging\nimport re\nimport time\nfrom typing import Annotated, cast\nfrom uuid import UUID, uuid4\n\nimport httpx\nfrom fastapi import HTTPException","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py","text":"\"\"\"MCP (Model Context Protocol) server for MemClaw.\n\nExposes MemClaw tools over Streamable HTTP so any MCP client\n(Claude Desktop, Claude Code, Cursor, etc.) can connect with just a URL + API key.\n\nMounted onto the main FastAPI app at /mcp.\n\"\"\"\n\nimport contextlib\nimport contextvars\nimport hmac as _hmac\nimport json\nimport logging\nimport re\nimport time\nfrom typing import Annotated, cast\nfrom uuid import UUID, uuid4\n\nimport httpx\nfrom fastapi import HTTPException\nfrom mcp.server.fastmcp import FastMCP\nfrom mcp.server.transport_security import TransportSecuritySettings\nfrom mcp.types import CallToolResult, TextContent\nfrom pydantic import Field, ValidationError\nfrom sqlalchemy import text as sa_text\nfrom starlette.types import ASGIApp, Receive, Scope, Send\n\nfrom common.enrichment.constants import SERVER_RESERVED_MEMORY_TYPES\nfrom core_api.auth import get_admin_key\nfrom core_api.clients.storage_client import KeystoneUpsertPayload, get_storage_client\nfrom core_api.constants import (\n    DEFAULT_SEARCH_TOP_K,\n    EVOLVE_OUTCOME_TYPES,\n    INSIGHTS_FOCUS_MODES,\n    MAX_SEARCH_TOP_K,\n    MEMORY_STATUSES,\n    MEMORY_TYPES,\n    VALID_SCOPES,\n    VERSION,\n)\nfrom core_api.db.session import async_session\nfrom core_api.errors import code_for_status\nfrom core_api.repositories import memory_repo\nfrom core_api.schemas import BulkMemoryCreate, BulkMemoryItem, MemoryCreate, MemoryUpdate\nfrom core_api.services.agent_service import (\n    authorize_memory_access,\n    enforce_delete,\n    enforce_fleet_read,\n    enforce_fleet_write,\n)\nfrom core_api.services.audit_service import log_action, log_cross_tenant_read\nfrom core_api.services.entity_service import get_entity\nfrom core_api.services.memory_service import (\n    create_memories_bulk,\n    create_memory,\n    search_memories,\n    soft_delete_memory,\n    update_memory,\n)\n\n# Re-export so existing `monkeypatch.setattr(mcp_server, \"_require_trust\", ...)`\n# sites in tests keep working; production callers should import ``require_trust``\n# directly from ``core_api.services.trust_service``.\nfrom core_api.services.trust_service import parse_trust_error\nfrom core_api.services.trust_service import require_trust as _require_trust\nfrom core_api.services.usage_service import check_and_increment_by_tenant as check_and_increment\nfrom core_api.trust_utils import effective_keystone_min_trust, keystone_min_trust\n\nlogger = logging.getLogger(__name__)\n\n# ── Auth via context vars ──\n\n_tenant_id_var: contextvars.ContextVar[str] = contextvars.ContextVar(\"mcp_tenant_id\")\n_agent_id_var: contextvars.ContextVar[str | None] = contextvars.ContextVar(\"mcp_agent_id\", default=None)\n# True iff X-Tenant-ID arrived as a request header (gateway-routed). On that\n# path the gateway is the source of truth for identity; falling back to the\n# literal \"mcp-agent\" tool-param default would silently attribute every write\n# from a tenant-key holder to a single shared identity (friction §2.8 / Stage 6b).\n_via_gateway_var: contextvars.ContextVar[bool] = contextvars.ContextVar(\"mcp_via_gateway\", default=False)\n# Cross-tenant read set plumbed from X-Readable-Tenant-IDs (CSV). Empty list\n# means single-tenant key (reads pinned to ``_tenant_id_var``). When populated\n# the home tenant_id is the first element and writes still go there.\n_readable_tenant_ids_var: contextvars.ContextVar[list[str] | None] = contextvars.ContextVar(\n    \"mcp_readable_tenant_ids\", default=None\n)\n_scopes_var: contextvars.ContextVar[set[str] | None] = contextvars.ContextVar(\"mcp_scopes\", default=None)\n\n_UNAUTH = \"__unauthenticated__\"\n_ADMIN = \"__admin__\"\n_NO_AUTH = \"__no_auth__\"\n_DEFAULT_AGENT_ID = \"mcp-agent\"\n\n\ndef _error_response(code: str, message: str, **details) -> str:\n    \"\"\"Return the canonical MCP error envelope as a JSON string.\n\n    Shape matches the REST surface (see ``core_api.errors.make_error_payload``):\n    ``{\"error\": {\"code\": \"...\", \"message\": \"...\", \"details\": {...}}}``.\n\n    The string is wrapped into a ``CallToolResult(isError=True)`` before\n    leaving the tool — either by ``_with_latency`` (which detects the\n    error shape) or by ``_as_error_result`` for pre-tool returns that\n    skip the latency stamp. Tool callsites keep returning plain strings;\n    the wrap happens at one of those two chokepoints (CAURA-000,\n    FRICTION-REPORT-V3 B2 — clients literal-reading the MCP spec were\n    seeing ``isError=False`` on every gateway-side refusal).\n    \"\"\"\n    from core_api.errors import make_error_payload\n\n    payload = make_error_payload(code, message, details=details if details else None)\n    return json.dumps(payload, default=str)\n\n\ndef _as_error_result(envelope: str) -> CallToolResult:\n    \"\"\"Wrap a ``_error_response`` JSON envelope into a CallToolResult\n    with ``isError=True``. The envelope JSON is preserved verbatim in\n    a single TextContent so callers reading ``result.content[0].text``\n    still get the structured payload. Used for the pre-tool / auth\n    return paths that don't run through ``_with_latency``.\n    \"\"\"\n    return CallToolResult(\n        content=[TextContent(type=\"text\", text=envelope)],\n        isError=True,\n    )\n\n\n# Pre-tool auth errors (returned directly, NOT through _with_latency, because\n# they fire before any tool work has begun, so we wrap them as\n# CallToolResults at module load — every tool that returns one\n# propagates ``isError=True`` to the MCP client.\n_AUTH_ERROR = _as_error_result(\n    _error_response(\n        \"UNAUTHORIZED\",\n        \"Missing or invalid X-API-Key header. Provide a tenant-scoped API key.\",\n    )\n)\n_ADMIN_ERROR = _as_error_result(\n    _error_response(\n        \"FORBIDDEN\",\n        \"Admin/system keys cannot be used with MCP. Use a tenant-scoped API key.\",\n    )\n)\n\n\nclass MCPAuthMiddleware:\n    \"\"\"ASGI middleware that resolves X-API-Key to tenant_id before MCP handlers run.\"\"\"\n\n    def __init__(self, app: ASGIApp):\n        self.app = app\n\n    async def __call__(self, scope: Scope, receive: Receive, send: Send):\n        if scope[\"type\"] == \"http\":\n            from core_api.config import settings\n\n            headers = dict(scope.get(\"headers\", []))\n\n            # Preferred path: enterprise nginx has already validated the\n            # session cookie / JWT / API key via auth_request and injected\n            # X-Tenant-ID. Trust that resolution verbatim — otherwise a\n            # browser dashboard call (which sends `Authorization: Bearer\n            # <session JWT>` alongside the gateway-injected X-Tenant-ID)\n            # falls into the Authorization→api_key fallback below, fails\n            # the admin-key comparison, and reports UNAUTH despite the\n            # gateway having already approved the caller.\n            tenant_header = headers.get(b\"x-tenant-id\", b\"\").decode()\n            if tenant_header:\n                _tenant_id_var.set(tenant_header)\n                _via_gateway_var.set(True)\n            else:\n                _via_gateway_var.set(False)\n                api_key = headers.get(b\"x-api-key\", b\"\").decode()\n                if not api_key:\n                    auth_header = headers.get(b\"authorization\", b\"\").decode()\n                    if auth_header.lower().startswith(\"bearer \"):\n                        api_key = auth_header[7:]\n                admin_key = get_admin_key()\n\n                if admin_key and api_key and _hmac.compare_digest(api_key, admin_key):\n                    _tenant_id_var.set(_ADMIN)\n                elif settings.is_standalone:\n                    from core_api.standalone import get_standalone_tenant_id\n\n                    _tenant_id_var.set(get_standalone_tenant_id())\n                elif not api_key:\n                    _tenant_id_var.set(_UNAUTH if admin_key else _NO_AUTH)\n                else:\n                    _tenant_id_var.set(_UNAUTH)\n\n            # X-Agent-ID injected by enterprise gateway for agent-scoped\n            # credentials (kind=agent_key). When present, this is the\n            # cryptographically verified agent identity.\n            agent_header = headers.get(b\"x-agent-id\", b\"\").decode()\n            _agent_id_var.set(agent_header or None)\n\n            # X-Readable-Tenant-IDs and X-Key-Scopes are plumbed by the gateway\n            # for credentials authorized to read beyond their home tenant\n            # (cross-tenant agent keys). Absent / empty headers leave the\n            # context vars at their single-tenant defaults.\n            # Always reset both context vars at the start of every request,\n            # not just when the header is present. ContextVars set inside a\n            # prior request can survive into the next request when the\n            # underlying ASGI task is reused or the var was never assigned a\n            # token-based reset. An absent header means \"single-tenant /\n            # full-scope\" — make that explicit so a previous request's\n            # cross-tenant read-set or read-only scope cannot bleed through.\n            readable_header = headers.get(b\"x-readable-tenant-ids\", b\"\").decode()\n            _readable_tenant_ids_var.set(\n                [t.strip() for t in readable_header.split(\",\") if t.strip()] if readable_header else None\n            )\n            # X-Capabilities is canonical from the unified auth-api;\n            # X-Key-Scopes is accepted as a back-compat alias during\n            # the gateway rollout window.\n            caps_header = (\n                headers.get(b\"x-capabilities\", b\"\").decode() or headers.get(b\"x-key-scopes\", b\"\").decode()\n            )\n            _scopes_var.set({s.strip() for s in caps_header.split(\",\") if s.strip()} if caps_header else None)\n\n        await self.app(scope, receive, send)\n\n\ndef _get_tenant() -> str:\n    return _tenant_id_var.get(_UNAUTH)\n\n\ndef _get_agent_id() -> str | None:\n    \"\"\"Return the verified agent_id from X-Agent-ID header, or None.\"\"\"\n    return _agent_id_var.get(None)\n\n\ndef _get_readable_tenants() -> list[str]:\n    \"\"\"Return the cross-tenant read set; empty for single-tenant keys.\"\"\"\n    return _readable_tenant_ids_var.get(None) or []\n\n\ndef _get_scopes() -> set[str] | None:\n    \"\"\"Return the credential's scope set, or None for full-scope (legacy) keys.\"\"\"\n    return _scopes_var.get(None)\n\n\ndef _is_write_allowed() -> bool:\n    \"\"\"Return False if the active credential is scope-limited to read-only.\"\"\"\n    scopes = _get_scopes()\n    if scopes is None:\n        return True\n    return \"write\" in scopes\n\n\ndef _refuse_default_agent_on_gateway(agent_id: str) -> str | None:\n    \"\"\"When the request came through the enterprise gateway (X-Tenant-ID set)\n    and the gateway didn't inject X-Agent-ID (mc_ tenant-key path), the caller\n    must supply a real agent_id. Falling back to the reserved ``\"mcp-agent\"``\n    default would silently attribute every write from a tenant-key holder to\n    one shared identity — the failure mode the friction report's bug repro\n    documented as ``agent row missing from list_agents``.\n\n    Returns an error envelope if the call should be refused; ``None`` to proceed.\n    Standalone, admin, and gateway-routed agent-scoped paths are unaffected:\n    standalone uses a stable single-tenant identity, admin is a system caller,\n    and an agent-scoped credential resolves X-Agent-ID via auth_validate so\n    this guard never fires for it.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":260,"totalLines":2542,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py","time":{"start":1780728390060,"end":1780728390071}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_06a9a7f5e5b14fe9016a23c245ec1c81919cfdb1c20def59d8"}},"id":"prt_e9baee197001N6a0APdSPJ3E6O","sessionID":"ses_164517a7bffeIaaPynAQONhoL2","messageID":"msg_e9bae8aca0016US3GawQg7j66u"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780728390117,"sessionID":"ses_164517a7bffeIaaPynAQONhoL2","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_20yCWXSmJ6DkpUKNRZLRLFiW","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/README.md","offset":1,"limit":320},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/README.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: <p align=\"center\">\n2:   <img src=\"static/images/memCLAW_logo_dark.png\" alt=\"MemClaw\" width=\"420\" />\n3: </p>\n4: \n5: <h3 align=\"center\">Fleet memory for AI agents &mdash; governed, shared, self-improving.</h3>\n6: \n7: <p align=\"center\">\n8:   <a href=\"LICENSE\"><img src=\"https://img.shields.io/badge/License-Apache_2.0-blue.svg\" alt=\"License\" /></a>\n9:   <a href=\"https://github.com/caura-ai/caura-memclaw/stargazers\"><img src=\"https://img.shields.io/github/stars/caura-ai/caura-memclaw?style=social\" alt=\"GitHub Stars\" /></a>\n10:   <a href=\"https://github.com/caura-ai/caura-memclaw/actions\"><img src=\"https://img.shields.io/github/actions/workflow/status/caura-ai/caura-memclaw/ci.yml?label=CI\" alt=\"CI\" /></a>\n11:   <a href=\"https://github.com/caura-ai/caura-memclaw/releases\"><img src=\"https://img.shields.io/github/v/release/caura-ai/caura-memclaw\" alt=\"Release\" /></a>\n12:   <a href=\"https://discord.com/invite/aNfpgfpj\"><img src=\"https://img.shields.io/badge/Discord-join-5865F2?logo=discord&logoColor=white\" alt=\"Join us on Discord\" /></a>\n13: </p>\n14: \n15: <p align=\"center\">\n16:   <a href=\"#quick-start\">Quick Start</a> &middot;\n17:   <a href=\"#features\">Features</a> &middot;\n18:   <a href=\"#performance\">Performance</a> &middot;\n19:   <a href=\"#mcp-model-context-protocol\">MCP</a> &middot;\n20:   <a href=\"#api-reference\">API Reference</a> &middot;\n21:   <a href=\"static/docs/integration-guide.md\">Plugin Docs</a> &middot;\n22:   <a href=\"CONTRIBUTING.md\">Contributing</a> &middot;\n23:   <a href=\"https://discord.com/invite/aNfpgfpj\">Discord</a>\n24: </p>\n25: \n26: ---\n27: \n28: ## MemClaw — Fleet memory for AI agents\n29: \n30: MemClaw is open-source memory for **multi-tenant, multi-agent** AI fleets. Your agents store what they learn, find what the fleet knows, and get smarter with every interaction — learning from each other instead of repeating mistakes.\n31: \n32: Agents write plain text. MemClaw turns it into searchable, governed, self-improving memory.\n33: \n34: **One loop, three pillars: write, recall, compound** — every interaction makes the next one smarter.\n35: \n36: **Built for fleets, not single agents.** Public agent-memory benchmarks (LoCoMo, LongMemEval) measure one agent, one user, one long conversation — the single-chatbot shape. The deployment shape we see in production is the opposite: dozens or thousands of agents working on behalf of a company, sharing what they learn under governance. MemClaw is architected around that shape from day one — scoped memory, cross-agent outcome propagation, fleet-wide trust tiers — and competes on the axes that compound with agent count: latency, token efficiency, and governance. See [Performance](#performance) for the numbers, or read the [benchmarks write-up](https://memclaw.net/blog/memclaw-benchmarks).\n37: \n38: <p align=\"center\">\n39:   <img src=\"static/images/memclaw-concept.svg\" alt=\"MemClaw — Fleet Memory that Compounds\" width=\"700\" />\n40: </p>\n41: \n42: ---\n43: \n44: ## Quick Start\n45: \n46: Three paths — pick the one that matches your setup:\n47: \n48: | Path | When | Time to first memory |\n49: |---|---|---|\n50: | **Managed platform** | Quickest. We host the DB + scaling. | ~2 min |\n51: | **Self-hosted (Docker)** | Privacy / on-prem / air-gapped. | ~5 min |\n52: | **OpenClaw plugin** | You already run an OpenClaw fleet — install MemClaw as a plugin against any of the above. | ~3 min |\n53: \n54: ### Managed Platform\n55: \n56: Get up and running in minutes — no infrastructure, automatic updates, usage analytics, and enterprise-grade security included.\n57: \n58: 1. **[Sign up free on memclaw.net](https://memclaw.net)**\n59: 2. Grab your API key from the dashboard\n60: 3. Connect via MCP or REST:\n61: \n62: ```json\n63: {\n64:   \"mcpServers\": {\n65:     \"memclaw\": {\n66:       \"url\": \"https://memclaw.net/mcp\",\n67:       \"headers\": { \"X-API-Key\": \"mc_your_api_key_here\" }\n68:     }\n69:   }\n70: }\n71: ```\n72: \n73: > **Production / team use:** the quickstart key above is a **tenant-scoped credential** — fine for personal use, but a fleet of agents should bind each one to its own **agent-scoped credential** for trust gating, fleet membership, and per-agent keystones. Provision agent-scoped credentials atomically via [`POST /api/v1/admin/agent-keys/provision`](docs/integration-without-plugin.md), or through the dashboard at `/settings/organization/api-credentials`. Both kinds use the `mc_` prefix on the wire — scope is bound at mint time on the credential itself. The MCP server accepts the credential on either `X-API-Key: mc_…` or `Authorization: Bearer mc_…`. *(Pre-existing `mca_…` and `mci_…` keys continue to authenticate via back-compat.)*\n74: >\n75: > Using a tenant-scoped credential? Pass an explicit `agent_id` on every MCP tool call — the gateway refuses the reserved default (`mcp-agent`) on the tenant-scoped path.\n76: \n77: ### Self-Hosted (Open Source)\n78: \n79: The fastest path is Docker Compose — one command brings up Postgres + pgvector + Redis + the API.\n80: \n81: > **Prefer not to use Docker?** Skip to [Manual deployment (Python + Postgres)](#manual-deployment) below for the bare-Python path.\n82: >\n83: > **No cloud API key, no external calls?** v2.0+ supports a self-hosted local embedder (`BAAI/bge-m3` via HuggingFace TEI) — see [`docs/local-embedder.md`](docs/local-embedder.md). The setup below walks through the OpenAI default; the local-embedder doc walks through the alternative.\n84: \n85: #### Prerequisites\n86: \n87: - **Docker Engine 24+** (Linux) or **Docker Desktop** (macOS / Windows). Confirm with `docker --version`.\n88: - **Docker Compose v2** (built into modern Docker). Confirm with `docker compose version`.\n89: - **Git** for cloning.\n90: - ~2 GB free disk for images + Postgres data volume.\n91: \n92: #### 1. Clone and configure\n93: \n94: ```bash\n95: git clone https://github.com/caura-ai/caura-memclaw.git\n96: cd caura-memclaw\n97: cp .env.example .env\n98: ```\n99: \n100: Set your AI provider in `.env` — minimal setup with OpenAI:\n101: \n102: ```env\n103: EMBEDDING_PROVIDER=openai\n104: ENTITY_EXTRACTION_PROVIDER=openai\n105: USE_LLM_FOR_MEMORY_CREATION=true\n106: OPENAI_API_KEY=sk-...\n107: ```\n108: \n109: > Without any AI keys the stack still starts — dummy providers return non-semantic embeddings, useful for testing the API surface.\n110: \n111: > 💡 **Want zero cloud API calls?** v2.0+ ships a self-hosted embedder\n112: > profile (`BAAI/bge-m3` on a [HuggingFace TEI](https://github.com/huggingface/text-embeddings-inference)\n113: > sidecar). Bring up the stack with `docker compose --profile embed-local up -d`\n114: > and set the four `OPENAI_EMBEDDING_*` envs from `.env.example` — see\n115: > [`docs/local-embedder.md`](docs/local-embedder.md) for the full setup.\n116: > Combined with `IS_STANDALONE=true` (below) this is a fully self-contained\n117: > deployment with no external API calls.\n118: \n119: <details>\n120: <summary>Other providers (Gemini, Anthropic, OpenRouter, self-hosted)</summary>\n121: \n122: | Provider | `.env` settings | Required key |\n123: |---|---|---|\n124: | **OpenAI** (default) | `EMBEDDING_PROVIDER=openai`<br>`ENTITY_EXTRACTION_PROVIDER=openai` | `OPENAI_API_KEY` |\n125: | **Google Gemini** | `EMBEDDING_PROVIDER=openai`<br>`ENTITY_EXTRACTION_PROVIDER=gemini` | `GEMINI_API_KEY` + `OPENAI_API_KEY` |\n126: | **Anthropic** | `EMBEDDING_PROVIDER=openai`<br>`ENTITY_EXTRACTION_PROVIDER=anthropic` | `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` + `OPENAI_API_KEY` |\n127: | **OpenRouter** | `EMBEDDING_PROVIDER=openai`<br>`ENTITY_EXTRACTION_PROVIDER=openrouter` | `OPENROUTER_API_KEY` + `OPENAI_API_KEY` |\n128: | **Self-hosted (TEI / bge-m3)** | `--profile embed-local` + `OPENAI_EMBEDDING_BASE_URL=http://tei:80/v1`<br>+ `OPENAI_EMBEDDING_MODEL=BAAI/bge-m3`<br>+ `OPENAI_EMBEDDING_SEND_DIMENSIONS=false` | none — runs locally |\n129: \n130: Anthropic, Gemini, and OpenRouter don't offer embedding APIs here — pair them with OpenAI (or with TEI) for embeddings. You can mix providers freely. Gemini uses the [Google AI Studio](https://aistudio.google.com/) key-auth Developer API (no GCP project/ADC required). The self-hosted TEI row keeps `EMBEDDING_PROVIDER=openai` because TEI speaks the same OpenAI-compatible API; see [`docs/local-embedder.md`](docs/local-embedder.md) for hardware sizing, GPU setup, and model swapping.\n131: \n132: </details>\n133: \n134: #### 2. Start the stack\n135: \n136: ```bash\n137: docker compose up -d\n138: ```\n139: \n140: By default this **pulls the multi-arch images from `ghcr.io`** (`linux/amd64` + `linux/arm64`) on first run — takes ~30 seconds. Subsequent `up` commands re-use the cached image (no registry round-trip, works offline). To pin a specific version, set `MEMCLAW_VERSION=v1.2.3` in your `.env`. To build from local source instead (e.g. when iterating on a fork), run `docker compose up --build --no-pull`.\n141: \n142: To upgrade to a newer image at the same tag (e.g. `:latest` after we cut a new release), run `docker compose pull && docker compose up -d`. Without an explicit `pull`, the local cache wins — there's no silent version drift.\n143: \n144: > **Offline / air-gapped operation**: depending on whether the image is already cached locally:\n145: > - **Image cached, no network**: `docker compose up -d` works as-is — `pull_policy: missing` doesn't try to pull when the image is present. Use `docker compose up --no-pull` if you want to be explicit.\n146: > - **No local image, no network**: `docker compose up --build --no-pull` (build from source, don't try to pull).\n147: > - **Strict no-network guarantee** (e.g. an air-gapped pipeline that should never reach `ghcr.io`): drop a `docker-compose.override.yml` setting `pull_policy: never` for both services — Compose then fails fast if the image is absent rather than attempting a pull.\n148: \n149: | Service | URL |\n150: |---|---|\n151: | Core API (REST + MCP) | http://localhost:8000 |\n152: | Core Storage API | http://localhost:8002 |\n153: | PostgreSQL (pgvector) | localhost:5432 |\n154: | Redis | localhost:6379 |\n155: \n156: #### 3. Verify\n157: \n158: ```bash\n159: curl http://localhost:8000/api/v1/health\n160: # {\"status\":\"ok\",\"database\":\"connected\",...}\n161: ```\n162: \n163: #### 4. Write and search\n164: \n165: ```bash\n166: # Write a memory (standalone mode — no API key needed)\n167: curl -X POST http://localhost:8000/api/v1/memories \\\n168:   -H \"X-API-Key: standalone\" \\\n169:   -H \"Content-Type: application/json\" \\\n170:   -d '{\"tenant_id\": \"default\", \"content\": \"Our auth service uses JWT with 15-minute expiry.\"}'\n171: \n172: # Search for it\n173: curl -X POST http://localhost:8000/api/v1/search \\\n174:   -H \"X-API-Key: standalone\" \\\n175:   -H \"Content-Type: application/json\" \\\n176:   -d '{\"tenant_id\": \"default\", \"query\": \"authentication token lifetime\"}'\n177: ```\n178: \n179: The write response includes LLM-inferred `type`, `title`, `summary`, `tags`, `status`, and `importance_score` — all from a single `content` field.\n180: \n181: <details>\n182: <summary>Auth modes</summary>\n183: \n184: OSS supports three auth paths. Pick one and add it to your `.env`, then `docker compose up -d` to restart.\n185: \n186: **Standalone** — single-tenant (`tenant_id=\"default\"`), simplest for local / self-install:\n187: ```env\n188: IS_STANDALONE=true\n189: ```\n190: No API key required for REST. MCP still expects a non-empty `X-API-Key` header — any value works.\n191: \n192: > Pair Standalone mode with `--profile embed-local` (see [`docs/local-embedder.md`](docs/local-embedder.md)) for a fully self-contained deployment: no admin keys, no external API calls, all embeddings computed locally. Useful for offline / air-gapped environments and personal-laptop installs.\n193: \n194: **Admin key** — multi-tenant with full access:\n195: ```env\n196: ADMIN_API_KEY=your-long-random-admin-key\n197: ```\n198: Pass `X-API-Key: your-long-random-admin-key` and include `tenant_id` in request bodies / query params.\n199: \n200: **Shared gate** — for network-exposed OSS deployments:\n201: ```env\n202: MEMCLAW_API_KEY=your-shared-key\n203: ```\n204: Clients send `X-API-Key: your-shared-key` plus `X-Tenant-ID: <tenant>`.\n205: \n206: > See [AGENT-INSTALL.md](AGENT-INSTALL.md) for the full agent self-install walkthrough.\n207: \n208: </details>\n209: \n210: <details>\n211: <summary>Running tests</summary>\n212: \n213: ```bash\n214: # Unit tests (no DB needed)\n215: pytest tests/ -m \"unit\"\n216: \n217: # All tests (requires PostgreSQL)\n218: docker compose up -d db\n219: pytest tests/ -m \"not benchmark\"\n220: \n221: # Smoke test against live API (~30s, auto-cleanup)\n222: python scripts/smoke_test.py --url http://localhost:8000 --api-key <admin-key>\n223: ```\n224: \n225: </details>\n226: \n227: ### OpenClaw Plugin\n228: \n229: Already running an OpenClaw fleet? Install MemClaw as a plugin against either the managed platform or your self-hosted stack:\n230: \n231: ```bash\n232: # Point at whichever URL hosts your MemClaw API\n233: export MEMCLAW_URL=https://memclaw.net          # managed\n234: # or:  export MEMCLAW_URL=http://localhost:8000  # self-hosted\n235: export MEMCLAW_KEY=your-key                      # `standalone` works in self-hosted standalone mode\n236: export MEMCLAW_FLEET=my-fleet\n237: \n238: curl -sf -H \"X-API-Key: $MEMCLAW_KEY\" \\\n239:   \"$MEMCLAW_URL/api/v1/install-plugin?fleet_id=$MEMCLAW_FLEET&api_url=$MEMCLAW_URL\" | bash\n240: \n241: # Restart the gateway to load the plugin\n242: openclaw gateway restart\n243: ```\n244: \n245: The plugin claims the OpenClaw `memory` slot (replacing `memory-core`) and exposes the same 12 MCP tools. Full setup, agent prompts, and trust levels: [static/docs/integration-guide.md](static/docs/integration-guide.md).\n246: \n247: ---\n248: \n249: ## Features\n250: \n251: ### Governance\n252: \n253: - **Tenant isolation** — row-level database separation per tenant; PII auto-detected and quarantined before it can cross fleet boundaries\n254: - **Visibility scopes** — every memory is stamped at write time: `scope_agent` (private), `scope_team` (fleet-wide, default), or `scope_org` (cross-fleet). Cross-fleet recall is permissioned, not open\n255: - **Agent trust tiers** — four levels control cross-fleet reads, writes, and deletes. Agents are either provisioned atomically via `POST /admin/agent-keys/provision` (recommended — mints key + row + trust + fleet in one call) or auto-registered on first write (legacy fallback)\n256: - **Full audit log** — every write, delete, and transition logged with tenant and scope context\n257: \n258: ### Memory Pipeline\n259: \n260: - **Single-pass LLM enrichment** — every write auto-classifies into one of 14 memory types, generates title/summary/tags, scores importance, flags PII, and extracts entities — from a single `content` field\n261: - **Hybrid search** — pgvector semantic similarity + full-text keyword matching + knowledge graph expansion (up to 2 hops), ranked by composite score of similarity, importance, freshness, and graph boost\n262: - **Live knowledge graph** — people, orgs, locations, and concepts extracted into entities and relations on every write. Semantic entity resolution (>0.85 cosine) auto-merges duplicates\n263: - **Contradiction detection** — RDF triple comparison + LLM semantic analysis detects conflicting memories and automatically supersedes them, with full contradiction chain tracking\n264: \n265: ### Self-Improving Memory\n266: \n267: - **Outcome-based learning (Karpathy Loop)** — agents report success/failure after acting on recalled memories; the system reinforces what works and auto-generates preventive `rule`-type memories on failure\n268: - **Crystallization** — LLM merges near-duplicate memories into canonical atomic facts with full provenance; 8-status lifecycle automation retires stale data\n269: - **Per-agent retrieval tuning** — each agent optimizes its own retrieval profile (top_k, min_similarity, graph_max_hops, blend weights) from feedback, so search quality compounds with every interaction\n270: \n271: ### Integrations\n272: \n273: - **MCP server** — built-in [Model Context Protocol](https://modelcontextprotocol.io) at `/mcp` (Streamable HTTP). Connect Claude Desktop, Claude Code, Cursor, Windsurf, or any MCP client with a URL and API key\n274: - **Multi-provider LLM** — primary + fallback provider chain per tenant (OpenAI, Gemini, Anthropic, OpenRouter) with platform defaults for zero-config tenants\n275: - **Document store** — structured JSONB collections alongside semantic memories for exact-field lookups (customer records, config, task lists)\n276: \n277: ---\n278: \n279: ## Performance\n280: \n281: Benchmarked against the two most-cited public agent-memory benchmarks. Methodology and operator-scale context live in [`docs/performance.md`](docs/performance.md); the full write-up is on the blog.\n282: \n283: |  | LoCoMo | LongMemEval | Search latency |\n284: |---|---|---|---|\n285: | Accuracy (LLM-judge) | **77.6%** | **72.5%** | — |\n286: | Token savings vs full context | **96.6%** | **98.2%** | — |\n287: | Latency | — | — | **23 ms p50 · 27 ms p95** |\n288: \n289: Accuracy sits inside the leading cluster across the field (Mem0, Zep, MemClaw — scores cluster in a narrow band). The axes we push hardest are latency and token efficiency, because those are the ones that compound as agent count grows — a few hundred ms of search latency disappears behind one LLM call, but bills millions of times a day across a fleet.\n290: \n291: > Single-agent benchmarks can't measure cross-agent recall, outcome propagation between agents, fleet-scoped visibility, or governance-aware retrieval. Those are the questions that decide whether a memory system is *deployable* inside a company. See [`docs/performance.md`](docs/performance.md#what-these-benchmarks-cant-measure).\n292: \n293: Source: [Fast, Token-Efficient, and Built for Fleets](https://memclaw.net/blog/memclaw-benchmarks) (2026-04-19).\n294: \n295: ---\n296: \n297: ## MCP (Model Context Protocol)\n298: \n299: Add MemClaw to any MCP client with one config block.\n300: \n301: **Self-hosted** (localhost):\n302: \n303: ```json\n304: {\n305:   \"mcpServers\": {\n306:     \"memclaw\": {\n307:       \"url\": \"http://localhost:8000/mcp\",\n308:       \"headers\": { \"X-API-Key\": \"standalone\" }\n309:     }\n310:   }\n311: }\n312: ```\n313: \n314: **Managed platform** (memclaw.net):\n315: \n316: ```json\n317: {\n318:   \"mcpServers\": {\n319:     \"memclaw\": {\n320:       \"url\": \"https://memclaw.net/mcp\",\n\n(Showing lines 1-320 of 965. Use offset=321 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"<p align=\"center\">\n  <img src=\"static/images/memCLAW_logo_dark.png\" alt=\"MemClaw\" width=\"420\" />\n</p>\n\n<h3 align=\"center\">Fleet memory for AI agents &mdash; governed, shared, self-improving.</h3>\n\n<p align=\"center\">\n  <a href=\"LICENSE\"><img src=\"https://img.shields.io/badge/License-Apache_2.0-blue.svg\" alt=\"License\" /></a>\n  <a href=\"https://github.com/caura-ai/caura-memclaw/stargazers\"><img src=\"https://img.shields.io/github/stars/caura-ai/caura-memclaw?style=social\" alt=\"GitHub Stars\" /></a>\n  <a href=\"https://github.com/caura-ai/caura-memclaw/actions\"><img src=\"https://img.shields.io/github/actions/workflow/status/caura-ai/caura-memclaw/ci.yml?label=CI\" alt=\"CI\" /></a>\n  <a href=\"https://github.com/caura-ai/caura-memclaw/releases\"><img src=\"https://img.shields.io/github/v/release/caura-ai/caura-memclaw\" alt=\"Release\" /></a>\n  <a href=\"https://discord.com/invite/aNfpgfpj\"><img src=\"https://img.shields.io/badge/Discord-join-5865F2?logo=discord&logoColor=white\" alt=\"Join us on Discord\" /></a>\n</p>\n\n<p align=\"center\">\n  <a href=\"#quick-start\">Quick Start</a> &middot;\n  <a href=\"#features\">Features</a> &middot;\n  <a href=\"#performance\">Performance</a> &middot;\n  <a href=\"#mcp-model-context-protocol\">MCP</a> &middot;\n  <a href=\"#api-reference\">API Reference</a> &middot;","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/README.md","text":"<p align=\"center\">\n  <img src=\"static/images/memCLAW_logo_dark.png\" alt=\"MemClaw\" width=\"420\" />\n</p>\n\n<h3 align=\"center\">Fleet memory for AI agents &mdash; governed, shared, self-improving.</h3>\n\n<p align=\"center\">\n  <a href=\"LICENSE\"><img src=\"https://img.shields.io/badge/License-Apache_2.0-blue.svg\" alt=\"License\" /></a>\n  <a href=\"https://github.com/caura-ai/caura-memclaw/stargazers\"><img src=\"https://img.shields.io/github/stars/caura-ai/caura-memclaw?style=social\" alt=\"GitHub Stars\" /></a>\n  <a href=\"https://github.com/caura-ai/caura-memclaw/actions\"><img src=\"https://img.shields.io/github/actions/workflow/status/caura-ai/caura-memclaw/ci.yml?label=CI\" alt=\"CI\" /></a>\n  <a href=\"https://github.com/caura-ai/caura-memclaw/releases\"><img src=\"https://img.shields.io/github/v/release/caura-ai/caura-memclaw\" alt=\"Release\" /></a>\n  <a href=\"https://discord.com/invite/aNfpgfpj\"><img src=\"https://img.shields.io/badge/Discord-join-5865F2?logo=discord&logoColor=white\" alt=\"Join us on Discord\" /></a>\n</p>\n\n<p align=\"center\">\n  <a href=\"#quick-start\">Quick Start</a> &middot;\n  <a href=\"#features\">Features</a> &middot;\n  <a href=\"#performance\">Performance</a> &middot;\n  <a href=\"#mcp-model-context-protocol\">MCP</a> &middot;\n  <a href=\"#api-reference\">API Reference</a> &middot;\n  <a href=\"static/docs/integration-guide.md\">Plugin Docs</a> &middot;\n  <a href=\"CONTRIBUTING.md\">Contributing</a> &middot;\n  <a href=\"https://discord.com/invite/aNfpgfpj\">Discord</a>\n</p>\n\n---\n\n## MemClaw — Fleet memory for AI agents\n\nMemClaw is open-source memory for **multi-tenant, multi-agent** AI fleets. Your agents store what they learn, find what the fleet knows, and get smarter with every interaction — learning from each other instead of repeating mistakes.\n\nAgents write plain text. MemClaw turns it into searchable, governed, self-improving memory.\n\n**One loop, three pillars: write, recall, compound** — every interaction makes the next one smarter.\n\n**Built for fleets, not single agents.** Public agent-memory benchmarks (LoCoMo, LongMemEval) measure one agent, one user, one long conversation — the single-chatbot shape. The deployment shape we see in production is the opposite: dozens or thousands of agents working on behalf of a company, sharing what they learn under governance. MemClaw is architected around that shape from day one — scoped memory, cross-agent outcome propagation, fleet-wide trust tiers — and competes on the axes that compound with agent count: latency, token efficiency, and governance. See [Performance](#performance) for the numbers, or read the [benchmarks write-up](https://memclaw.net/blog/memclaw-benchmarks).\n\n<p align=\"center\">\n  <img src=\"static/images/memclaw-concept.svg\" alt=\"MemClaw — Fleet Memory that Compounds\" width=\"700\" />\n</p>\n\n---\n\n## Quick Start\n\nThree paths — pick the one that matches your setup:\n\n| Path | When | Time to first memory |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Managed platform** | Quickest. We host the DB + scaling. | ~2 min |\n| **Self-hosted (Docker)** | Privacy / on-prem / air-gapped. | ~5 min |\n| **OpenClaw plugin** | You already run an OpenClaw fleet — install MemClaw as a plugin against any of the above. | ~3 min |\n\n### Managed Platform\n\nGet up and running in minutes — no infrastructure, automatic updates, usage analytics, and enterprise-grade security included.\n\n1. **[Sign up free on memclaw.net](https://memclaw.net)**\n2. Grab your API key from the dashboard\n3. Connect via MCP or REST:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"mcpServers\": {\n    \"memclaw\": {\n      \"url\": \"https://memclaw.net/mcp\",\n      \"headers\": { \"X-API-Key\": \"mc_your_api_key_here\" }\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n> **Production / team use:** the quickstart key above is a **tenant-scoped credential** — fine for personal use, but a fleet of agents should bind each one to its own **agent-scoped credential** for trust gating, fleet membership, and per-agent keystones. Provision agent-scoped credentials atomically via [`POST /api/v1/admin/agent-keys/provision`](docs/integration-without-plugin.md), or through the dashboard at `/settings/organization/api-credentials`. Both kinds use the `mc_` prefix on the wire — scope is bound at mint time on the credential itself. The MCP server accepts the credential on either `X-API-Key: mc_…` or `Authorization: Bearer mc_…`. *(Pre-existing `mca_…` and `mci_…` keys continue to authenticate via back-compat.)*\n>\n> Using a tenant-scoped credential? Pass an explicit `agent_id` on every MCP tool call — the gateway refuses the reserved default (`mcp-agent`) on the tenant-scoped path.\n\n### Self-Hosted (Open Source)\n\nThe fastest path is Docker Compose — one command brings up Postgres + pgvector + Redis + the API.\n\n> **Prefer not to use Docker?** Skip to [Manual deployment (Python + Postgres)](#manual-deployment) below for the bare-Python path.\n>\n> **No cloud API key, no external calls?** v2.0+ supports a self-hosted local embedder (`BAAI/bge-m3` via HuggingFace TEI) — see [`docs/local-embedder.md`](docs/local-embedder.md). The setup below walks through the OpenAI default; the local-embedder doc walks through the alternative.\n\n#### Prerequisites\n\n- **Docker Engine 24+** (Linux) or **Docker Desktop** (macOS / Windows). Confirm with `docker --version`.\n- **Docker Compose v2** (built into modern Docker). Confirm with `docker compose version`.\n- **Git** for cloning.\n- ~2 GB free disk for images + Postgres data volume.\n\n#### 1. Clone and configure\n\n```bash\ngit clone https://github.com/caura-ai/caura-memclaw.git\ncd caura-memclaw\ncp .env.example .env\n```\n\nSet your AI provider in `.env` — minimal setup with OpenAI:\n\n```env\nEMBEDDING_PROVIDER=openai\nENTITY_EXTRACTION_PROVIDER=openai\nUSE_LLM_FOR_MEMORY_CREATION=true\nOPENAI_API_KEY=sk-...\n```\n\n> Without any AI keys the stack still starts — dummy providers return non-semantic embeddings, useful for testing the API surface.\n\n> 💡 **Want zero cloud API calls?** v2.0+ ships a self-hosted embedder\n> profile (`BAAI/bge-m3` on a [HuggingFace TEI](https://github.com/huggingface/text-embeddings-inference)\n> sidecar). Bring up the stack with `docker compose --profile embed-local up -d`\n> and set the four `OPENAI_EMBEDDING_*` envs from `.env.example` — see\n> [`docs/local-embedder.md`](docs/local-embedder.md) for the full setup.\n> Combined with `IS_STANDALONE=true` (below) this is a fully self-contained\n> deployment with no external API calls.\n\n<details>\n<summary>Other providers (Gemini, Anthropic, OpenRouter, self-hosted)</summary>\n\n| Provider | `.env` settings | Required key |\n|---|---|---|\n| **OpenAI** (default) | `EMBEDDING_PROVIDER=openai`<br>`ENTITY_EXTRACTION_PROVIDER=openai` | `OPENAI_API_KEY` |\n| **Google Gemini** | `EMBEDDING_PROVIDER=openai`<br>`ENTITY_EXTRACTION_PROVIDER=gemini` | `GEMINI_API_KEY` + `OPENAI_API_KEY` |\n| **Anthropic** | `EMBEDDING_PROVIDER=openai`<br>`ENTITY_EXTRACTION_PROVIDER=anthropic` | `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` + `OPENAI_API_KEY` |\n| **OpenRouter** | `EMBEDDING_PROVIDER=openai`<br>`ENTITY_EXTRACTION_PROVIDER=openrouter` | `OPENROUTER_API_KEY` + `OPENAI_API_KEY` |\n| **Self-hosted (TEI / bge-m3)** | `--profile embed-local` + `OPENAI_EMBEDDING_BASE_URL=http://tei:80/v1`<br>+ `OPENAI_EMBEDDING_MODEL=BAAI/bge-m3`<br>+ `OPENAI_EMBEDDING_SEND_DIMENSIONS=false` | none — runs locally |\n\nAnthropic, Gemini, and OpenRouter don't offer embedding APIs here — pair them with OpenAI (or with TEI) for embeddings. You can mix providers freely. Gemini uses the [Google AI Studio](https://aistudio.google.com/) key-auth Developer API (no GCP project/ADC required). The self-hosted TEI row keeps `EMBEDDING_PROVIDER=openai` because TEI speaks the same OpenAI-compatible API; see [`docs/local-embedder.md`](docs/local-embedder.md) for hardware sizing, GPU setup, and model swapping.\n\n</details>\n\n#### 2. Start the stack\n\n```bash\ndocker compose up -d\n```\n\nBy default this **pulls the multi-arch images from `ghcr.io`** (`linux/amd64` + `linux/arm64`) on first run — takes ~30 seconds. Subsequent `up` commands re-use the cached image (no registry round-trip, works offline). To pin a specific version, set `MEMCLAW_VERSION=v1.2.3` in your `.env`. To build from local source instead (e.g. when iterating on a fork), run `docker compose up --build --no-pull`.\n\nTo upgrade to a newer image at the same tag (e.g. `:latest` after we cut a new release), run `docker compose pull && docker compose up -d`. Without an explicit `pull`, the local cache wins — there's no silent version drift.\n\n> **Offline / air-gapped operation**: depending on whether the image is already cached locally:\n> - **Image cached, no network**: `docker compose up -d` works as-is — `pull_policy: missing` doesn't try to pull when the image is present. Use `docker compose up --no-pull` if you want to be explicit.\n> - **No local image, no network**: `docker compose up --build --no-pull` (build from source, don't try to pull).\n> - **Strict no-network guarantee** (e.g. an air-gapped pipeline that should never reach `ghcr.io`): drop a `docker-compose.override.yml` setting `pull_policy: never` for both services — Compose then fails fast if the image is absent rather than attempting a pull.\n\n| Service | URL |\n|---|---|\n| Core API (REST + MCP) | http://localhost:8000 |\n| Core Storage API | http://localhost:8002 |\n| PostgreSQL (pgvector) | localhost:5432 |\n| Redis | localhost:6379 |\n\n#### 3. Verify\n\n```bash\ncurl http://localhost:8000/api/v1/health\n# {\"status\":\"ok\",\"database\":\"connected\",...}\n```\n\n#### 4. Write and search\n\n```bash\n# Write a memory (standalone mode — no API key needed)\ncurl -X POST http://localhost:8000/api/v1/memories \\\n  -H \"X-API-Key: standalone\" \\\n  -H \"Content-Type: application/json\" \\\n  -d '{\"tenant_id\": \"default\", \"content\": \"Our auth service uses JWT with 15-minute expiry.\"}'\n\n# Search for it\ncurl -X POST http://localhost:8000/api/v1/search \\\n  -H \"X-API-Key: standalone\" \\\n  -H \"Content-Type: application/json\" \\\n  -d '{\"tenant_id\": \"default\", \"query\": \"authentication token lifetime\"}'\n```\n\nThe write response includes LLM-inferred `type`, `title`, `summary`, `tags`, `status`, and `importance_score` — all from a single `content` field.\n\n<details>\n<summary>Auth modes</summary>\n\nOSS supports three auth paths. Pick one and add it to your `.env`, then `docker compose up -d` to restart.\n\n**Standalone** — single-tenant (`tenant_id=\"default\"`), simplest for local / self-install:\n```env\nIS_STANDALONE=true\n```\nNo API key required for REST. MCP still expects a non-empty `X-API-Key` header — any value works.\n\n> Pair Standalone mode with `--profile embed-local` (see [`docs/local-embedder.md`](docs/local-embedder.md)) for a fully self-contained deployment: no admin keys, no external API calls, all embeddings computed locally. Useful for offline / air-gapped environments and personal-laptop installs.\n\n**Admin key** — multi-tenant with full access:\n```env\nADMIN_API_KEY=your-long-random-admin-key\n```\nPass `X-API-Key: your-long-random-admin-key` and include `tenant_id` in request bodies / query params.\n\n**Shared gate** — for network-exposed OSS deployments:\n```env\nMEMCLAW_API_KEY=your-shared-key\n```\nClients send `X-API-Key: your-shared-key` plus `X-Tenant-ID: <tenant>`.\n\n> See [AGENT-INSTALL.md](AGENT-INSTALL.md) for the full agent self-install walkthrough.\n\n</details>\n\n<details>\n<summary>Running tests</summary>\n\n```bash\n# Unit tests (no DB needed)\npytest tests/ -m \"unit\"\n\n# All tests (requires PostgreSQL)\ndocker compose up -d db\npytest tests/ -m \"not benchmark\"\n\n# Smoke test against live API (~30s, auto-cleanup)\npython scripts/smoke_test.py --url http://localhost:8000 --api-key <admin-key>\n```\n\n</details>\n\n### OpenClaw Plugin\n\nAlready running an OpenClaw fleet? Install MemClaw as a plugin against either the managed platform or your self-hosted stack:\n\n```bash\n# Point at whichever URL hosts your MemClaw API\nexport MEMCLAW_URL=https://memclaw.net          # managed\n# or:  export MEMCLAW_URL=http://localhost:8000  # self-hosted\nexport MEMCLAW_KEY=your-key                      # `standalone` works in self-hosted standalone mode\nexport MEMCLAW_FLEET=my-fleet\n\ncurl -sf -H \"X-API-Key: $MEMCLAW_KEY\" \\\n  \"$MEMCLAW_URL/api/v1/install-plugin?fleet_id=$MEMCLAW_FLEET&api_url=$MEMCLAW_URL\" | bash\n\n# Restart the gateway to load the plugin\nopenclaw gateway restart\n```\n\nThe plugin claims the OpenClaw `memory` slot (replacing `memory-core`) and exposes the same 12 MCP tools. Full setup, agent prompts, and trust levels: [static/docs/integration-guide.md](static/docs/integration-guide.md).\n\n---\n\n## Features\n\n### Governance\n\n- **Tenant isolation** — row-level database separation per tenant; PII auto-detected and quarantined before it can cross fleet boundaries\n- **Visibility scopes** — every memory is stamped at write time: `scope_agent` (private), `scope_team` (fleet-wide, default), or `scope_org` (cross-fleet). Cross-fleet recall is permissioned, not open\n- **Agent trust tiers** — four levels control cross-fleet reads, writes, and deletes. Agents are either provisioned atomically via `POST /admin/agent-keys/provision` (recommended — mints key + row + trust + fleet in one call) or auto-registered on first write (legacy fallback)\n- **Full audit log** — every write, delete, and transition logged with tenant and scope context\n\n### Memory Pipeline\n\n- **Single-pass LLM enrichment** — every write auto-classifies into one of 14 memory types, generates title/summary/tags, scores importance, flags PII, and extracts entities — from a single `content` field\n- **Hybrid search** — pgvector semantic similarity + full-text keyword matching + knowledge graph expansion (up to 2 hops), ranked by composite score of similarity, importance, freshness, and graph boost\n- **Live knowledge graph** — people, orgs, locations, and concepts extracted into entities and relations on every write. Semantic entity resolution (>0.85 cosine) auto-merges duplicates\n- **Contradiction detection** — RDF triple comparison + LLM semantic analysis detects conflicting memories and automatically supersedes them, with full contradiction chain tracking\n\n### Self-Improving Memory\n\n- **Outcome-based learning (Karpathy Loop)** — agents report success/failure after acting on recalled memories; the system reinforces what works and auto-generates preventive `rule`-type memories on failure\n- **Crystallization** — LLM merges near-duplicate memories into canonical atomic facts with full provenance; 8-status lifecycle automation retires stale data\n- **Per-agent retrieval tuning** — each agent optimizes its own retrieval profile (top_k, min_similarity, graph_max_hops, blend weights) from feedback, so search quality compounds with every interaction\n\n### Integrations\n\n- **MCP server** — built-in [Model Context Protocol](https://modelcontextprotocol.io) at `/mcp` (Streamable HTTP). Connect Claude Desktop, Claude Code, Cursor, Windsurf, or any MCP client with a URL and API key\n- **Multi-provider LLM** — primary + fallback provider chain per tenant (OpenAI, Gemini, Anthropic, OpenRouter) with platform defaults for zero-config tenants\n- **Document store** — structured JSONB collections alongside semantic memories for exact-field lookups (customer records, config, task lists)\n\n---\n\n## Performance\n\nBenchmarked against the two most-cited public agent-memory benchmarks. Methodology and operator-scale context live in [`docs/performance.md`](docs/performance.md); the full write-up is on the blog.\n\n|  | LoCoMo | LongMemEval | Search latency |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Accuracy (LLM-judge) | **77.6%** | **72.5%** | — |\n| Token savings vs full context | **96.6%** | **98.2%** | — |\n| Latency | — | — | **23 ms p50 · 27 ms p95** |\n\nAccuracy sits inside the leading cluster across the field (Mem0, Zep, MemClaw — scores cluster in a narrow band). The axes we push hardest are latency and token efficiency, because those are the ones that compound as agent count grows — a few hundred ms of search latency disappears behind one LLM call, but bills millions of times a day across a fleet.\n\n> Single-agent benchmarks can't measure cross-agent recall, outcome propagation between agents, fleet-scoped visibility, or governance-aware retrieval. Those are the questions that decide whether a memory system is *deployable* inside a company. See [`docs/performance.md`](docs/performance.md#what-these-benchmarks-cant-measure).\n\nSource: [Fast, Token-Efficient, and Built for Fleets](https://memclaw.net/blog/memclaw-benchmarks) (2026-04-19).\n\n---\n\n## MCP (Model Context Protocol)\n\nAdd MemClaw to any MCP client with one config block.\n\n**Self-hosted** (localhost):\n\n```json\n{\n  \"mcpServers\": {\n    \"memclaw\": {\n      \"url\": \"http://localhost:8000/mcp\",\n      \"headers\": { \"X-API-Key\": \"standalone\" }\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Managed platform** (memclaw.net):\n\n```json\n{\n  \"mcpServers\": {\n    \"memclaw\": {\n      \"url\": \"https://memclaw.net/mcp\",","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":320,"totalLines":965,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/README.md","time":{"start":1780728390107,"end":1780728390116}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_06a9a7f5e5b14fe9016a23c245ec5081918137f881e9e93091"}},"id":"prt_e9baee1d9001kFp7mymeSAJ2cG","sessionID":"ses_164517a7bffeIaaPynAQONhoL2","messageID":"msg_e9bae8aca0016US3GawQg7j66u"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780728390119,"sessionID":"ses_164517a7bffeIaaPynAQONhoL2","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_76eG05mZM0oHKUnMelPRAs3p","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/plugin/openclaw.plugin.json","offset":1,"limit":220},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/plugin/openclaw.plugin.json</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: {\n2:   \"id\": \"memclaw\",\n3:   \"name\": \"MemClaw\",\n4:   \"kind\": \"memory\",\n5:   \"version\": \"2.8.0\",\n6:   \"description\": \"Central persistent memory for OpenClaw agents — write, search, and entity lookup tools.\",\n7:   \"entry\": \"dist/index.js\",\n8:   \"skills\": [\n9:     \"skills\"\n10:   ],\n11:   \"configSchema\": {\n12:     \"type\": \"object\",\n13:     \"properties\": {},\n14:     \"required\": []\n15:   },\n16:   \"contracts\": {\n17:     \"tools\": [\n18:       \"memclaw_recall\",\n19:       \"memclaw_write\",\n20:       \"memclaw_manage\",\n21:       \"memclaw_doc\",\n22:       \"memclaw_list\",\n23:       \"memclaw_entity_get\",\n24:       \"memclaw_tune\",\n25:       \"memclaw_insights\",\n26:       \"memclaw_evolve\",\n27:       \"memclaw_stats\",\n28:       \"memclaw_keystones\"\n29:     ]\n30:   }\n31: }\n\n(End of file - total 31 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"{\n  \"id\": \"memclaw\",\n  \"name\": \"MemClaw\",\n  \"kind\": \"memory\",\n  \"version\": \"2.8.0\",\n  \"description\": \"Central persistent memory for OpenClaw agents — write, search, and entity lookup tools.\",\n  \"entry\": \"dist/index.js\",\n  \"skills\": [\n    \"skills\"\n  ],\n  \"configSchema\": {\n    \"type\": \"object\",\n    \"properties\": {},\n    \"required\": []\n  },\n  \"contracts\": {\n    \"tools\": [\n      \"memclaw_recall\",\n      \"memclaw_write\",\n      \"memclaw_manage\",","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/plugin/openclaw.plugin.json","text":"{\n  \"id\": \"memclaw\",\n  \"name\": \"MemClaw\",\n  \"kind\": \"memory\",\n  \"version\": \"2.8.0\",\n  \"description\": \"Central persistent memory for OpenClaw agents — write, search, and entity lookup tools.\",\n  \"entry\": \"dist/index.js\",\n  \"skills\": [\n    \"skills\"\n  ],\n  \"configSchema\": {\n    \"type\": \"object\",\n    \"properties\": {},\n    \"required\": []\n  },\n  \"contracts\": {\n    \"tools\": [\n      \"memclaw_recall\",\n      \"memclaw_write\",\n      \"memclaw_manage\",\n      \"memclaw_doc\",\n      \"memclaw_list\",\n      \"memclaw_entity_get\",\n      \"memclaw_tune\",\n      \"memclaw_insights\",\n      \"memclaw_evolve\",\n      \"memclaw_stats\",\n      \"memclaw_keystones\"\n    ]\n  }\n}","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":31,"totalLines":31,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/plugin/openclaw.plugin.json","time":{"start":1780728390104,"end":1780728390118}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_06a9a7f5e5b14fe9016a23c245ec4481919a2508b60140eac9"}},"id":"prt_e9baee1d6001e28mLd0Jowkd14","sessionID":"ses_164517a7bffeIaaPynAQONhoL2","messageID":"msg_e9bae8aca0016US3GawQg7j66u"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780728390121,"sessionID":"ses_164517a7bffeIaaPynAQONhoL2","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_OYiqimRoUPXdsWnEmnbRgyXu","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/plugin/tools.json","offset":1,"limit":260},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/plugin/tools.json</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: [\n2:   {\n3:     \"description\": \"Structured-document CRUD in named collections. op: write|read|query|delete|list_collections|search. write upserts by collection+doc_id \\u2014 include data['summary'] (1-3 dense sentences, intent-focused) to make the doc semantically searchable; omit it to store without indexing. query filters by where dict; list_collections enumerates every collection this tenant has (with counts); search runs semantic retrieval over data['summary'] vectors \\u2014 pass collection to scope to one (narrow strategy), or omit collection to span every collection in the tenant (broad strategy). Use for structured records (customers, config). For memories use memclaw_write.\",\n4:     \"error_codes\": [\n5:       \"INVALID_ARGUMENTS\"\n6:     ],\n7:     \"impl_status\": \"live\",\n8:     \"name\": \"memclaw_doc\",\n9:     \"ops\": [\n10:       {\n11:         \"description\": \"Upsert a document by collection+doc_id. Set data['summary'] to a short (1-3 sentence) intent-focused description to make the doc semantically searchable \\u2014 that string (and only that string) is what gets embedded. The full body lives wherever the caller puts it (e.g. data['content']) and is returned in read/search results but is NOT indexed. Good: 'Postgres tuning runbook: vacuum, autovacuum, work_mem.' Bad: '<the first 200 chars of the body>' (truncation is not summarization). Omit summary to store the doc without indexing.\",\n12:         \"name\": \"write\",\n13:         \"required_params\": [\n14:           \"collection\",\n15:           \"doc_id\",\n16:           \"data\"\n17:         ],\n18:         \"trust_required\": 0\n19:       },\n20:       {\n21:         \"description\": \"Fetch a document by collection+doc_id.\",\n22:         \"name\": \"read\",\n23:         \"required_params\": [\n24:           \"collection\",\n25:           \"doc_id\"\n26:         ],\n27:         \"trust_required\": 0\n28:       },\n29:       {\n30:         \"description\": \"Filter documents by field equality.\",\n31:         \"name\": \"query\",\n32:         \"required_params\": [\n33:           \"collection\"\n34:         ],\n35:         \"trust_required\": 0\n36:       },\n37:       {\n38:         \"description\": \"Remove a document by collection+doc_id.\",\n39:         \"name\": \"delete\",\n40:         \"required_params\": [\n41:           \"collection\",\n42:           \"doc_id\"\n43:         ],\n44:         \"trust_required\": 0\n45:       },\n46:       {\n47:         \"description\": \"Enumerate every collection this tenant has written to, with per-collection document counts. No required params; optional fleet_id scopes counts to one fleet.\",\n48:         \"name\": \"list_collections\",\n49:         \"required_params\": [],\n50:         \"trust_required\": 0\n51:       },\n52:       {\n53:         \"description\": \"Semantic search. Pass collection to scope to one (narrow); omit collection to search every collection in the tenant (broad). Only docs written with a data['summary'] appear (no summary \\u2192 no embedding \\u2192 invisible to search). Returns up to top_k results ordered by cosine similarity (1.0 = identical). Each row includes its own collection so the caller can follow up with op=read.\",\n54:         \"name\": \"search\",\n55:         \"required_params\": [\n56:           \"query\"\n57:         ],\n58:         \"trust_required\": 0\n59:       }\n60:     ],\n61:     \"params\": [\n62:       {\n63:         \"description\": \"write|read|query|delete|list_collections|search.\",\n64:         \"name\": \"op\",\n65:         \"required\": true,\n66:         \"type\": \"str\"\n67:       },\n68:       {\n69:         \"default\": null,\n70:         \"description\": \"Collection. Required for write|read|query|delete|search; omitted for list_collections.\",\n71:         \"name\": \"collection\",\n72:         \"required\": false,\n73:         \"type\": \"str | None\"\n74:       },\n75:       {\n76:         \"default\": null,\n77:         \"description\": \"op=write|read|delete.\",\n78:         \"name\": \"doc_id\",\n79:         \"required\": false,\n80:         \"type\": \"str | None\"\n81:       },\n82:       {\n83:         \"default\": null,\n84:         \"description\": \"op=write.\",\n85:         \"name\": \"data\",\n86:         \"required\": false,\n87:         \"type\": \"dict | None\"\n88:       },\n89:       {\n90:         \"default\": null,\n91:         \"description\": \"op=query.\",\n92:         \"name\": \"where\",\n93:         \"required\": false,\n94:         \"type\": \"dict | None\"\n95:       },\n96:       {\n97:         \"default\": null,\n98:         \"description\": \"op=query.\",\n99:         \"name\": \"order_by\",\n100:         \"required\": false,\n101:         \"type\": \"str | None\"\n102:       },\n103:       {\n104:         \"default\": \"asc\",\n105:         \"description\": \"op=query: asc|desc.\",\n106:         \"name\": \"order\",\n107:         \"required\": false,\n108:         \"type\": \"str\"\n109:       },\n110:       {\n111:         \"default\": 20,\n112:         \"description\": \"op=query.\",\n113:         \"name\": \"limit\",\n114:         \"required\": false,\n115:         \"type\": \"int\"\n116:       },\n117:       {\n118:         \"default\": 0,\n119:         \"description\": \"op=query.\",\n120:         \"name\": \"offset\",\n121:         \"required\": false,\n122:         \"type\": \"int\"\n123:       },\n124:       {\n125:         \"default\": \"mcp-agent\",\n126:         \"description\": \"Caller agent.\",\n127:         \"name\": \"agent_id\",\n128:         \"required\": false,\n129:         \"type\": \"str\"\n130:       },\n131:       {\n132:         \"default\": null,\n133:         \"description\": \"op=write; optional scoping filter for op=list_collections|search.\",\n134:         \"name\": \"fleet_id\",\n135:         \"required\": false,\n136:         \"type\": \"str | None\"\n137:       },\n138:       {\n139:         \"default\": null,\n140:         \"description\": \"op=search: natural-language query.\",\n141:         \"name\": \"query\",\n142:         \"required\": false,\n143:         \"type\": \"str | None\"\n144:       },\n145:       {\n146:         \"default\": 5,\n147:         \"description\": \"op=search: max results (1-50).\",\n148:         \"name\": \"top_k\",\n149:         \"required\": false,\n150:         \"type\": \"int\"\n151:       }\n152:     ],\n153:     \"plugin_exposed\": true,\n154:     \"trust_required\": 0\n155:   },\n156:   {\n157:     \"description\": \"Look up an entity by UUID. Use only when you have an entity_id from a prior search.\",\n158:     \"error_codes\": [],\n159:     \"impl_status\": \"live\",\n160:     \"name\": \"memclaw_entity_get\",\n161:     \"ops\": [],\n162:     \"params\": [\n163:       {\n164:         \"description\": \"The UUID of the entity to look up.\",\n165:         \"name\": \"entity_id\",\n166:         \"required\": true,\n167:         \"type\": \"str\"\n168:       }\n169:     ],\n170:     \"plugin_exposed\": true,\n171:     \"trust_required\": 0\n172:   },\n173:   {\n174:     \"description\": \"Report what happened after acting on memories. outcome_type: success|failure|partial. related_ids = the memory UUIDs that influenced the action (use IDs from your most recent memclaw_recall). scope: agent (default, trust \\u2265 1)|fleet|all (trust \\u2265 2; fleet_id required when scope='fleet'). Weight adjustments and rule generation are scoped \\u2014 agents can only evolve memories they own (scope=agent), their fleet (scope=fleet), or any (scope=all).\",\n175:     \"error_codes\": [],\n176:     \"impl_status\": \"live\",\n177:     \"name\": \"memclaw_evolve\",\n178:     \"ops\": [],\n179:     \"params\": [\n180:       {\n181:         \"description\": \"Natural-language description of what happened.\",\n182:         \"name\": \"outcome\",\n183:         \"required\": true,\n184:         \"type\": \"str\"\n185:       },\n186:       {\n187:         \"description\": \"success|failure|partial.\",\n188:         \"name\": \"outcome_type\",\n189:         \"required\": true,\n190:         \"type\": \"str\"\n191:       },\n192:       {\n193:         \"default\": null,\n194:         \"description\": \"Memory UUIDs that influenced the action.\",\n195:         \"name\": \"related_ids\",\n196:         \"required\": false,\n197:         \"type\": \"list[str] | None\"\n198:       },\n199:       {\n200:         \"default\": \"agent\",\n201:         \"description\": \"agent|fleet|all.\",\n202:         \"name\": \"scope\",\n203:         \"required\": false,\n204:         \"type\": \"str\"\n205:       },\n206:       {\n207:         \"default\": \"mcp-agent\",\n208:         \"description\": \"Caller agent.\",\n209:         \"name\": \"agent_id\",\n210:         \"required\": false,\n211:         \"type\": \"str\"\n212:       },\n213:       {\n214:         \"default\": null,\n215:         \"description\": \"Required when scope='fleet'.\",\n216:         \"name\": \"fleet_id\",\n217:         \"required\": false,\n218:         \"type\": \"str | None\"\n219:       }\n220:     ],\n221:     \"plugin_exposed\": true,\n222:     \"trust_required\": 1\n223:   },\n224:   {\n225:     \"description\": \"Reflect over your memory store. focus: contradictions|failures|stale|divergence|patterns|discover. scope: agent (default, trust \\u2265 1)|fleet|all (trust \\u2265 2; divergence requires fleet/all). Findings are saved as insight-type memories for future runs to build on.\",\n226:     \"error_codes\": [],\n227:     \"impl_status\": \"live\",\n228:     \"name\": \"memclaw_insights\",\n229:     \"ops\": [],\n230:     \"params\": [\n231:       {\n232:         \"description\": \"contradictions|failures|stale|divergence|patterns|discover.\",\n233:         \"name\": \"focus\",\n234:         \"required\": true,\n235:         \"type\": \"str\"\n236:       },\n237:       {\n238:         \"default\": \"agent\",\n239:         \"description\": \"agent|fleet|all.\",\n240:         \"name\": \"scope\",\n241:         \"required\": false,\n242:         \"type\": \"str\"\n243:       },\n244:       {\n245:         \"default\": null,\n246:         \"description\": \"Required when scope='fleet'.\",\n247:         \"name\": \"fleet_id\",\n248:         \"required\": false,\n249:         \"type\": \"str | None\"\n250:       },\n251:       {\n252:         \"default\": \"mcp-agent\",\n253:         \"description\": \"Caller agent.\",\n254:         \"name\": \"agent_id\",\n255:         \"required\": false,\n256:         \"type\": \"str\"\n257:       }\n258:     ],\n259:     \"plugin_exposed\": true,\n260:     \"trust_required\": 1\n\n(Showing lines 1-260 of 925. Use offset=261 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"[\n  {\n    \"description\": \"Structured-document CRUD in named collections. op: write|read|query|delete|list_collections|search. write upserts by collection+doc_id \\u2014 include data['summary'] (1-3 dense sentences, intent-focused) to make the doc semantically searchable; omit it to store without indexing. query filters by where dict; list_collections enumerates every collection this tenant has (with counts); search runs semantic retrieval over data['summary'] vectors \\u2014 pass collection to scope to one (narrow strategy), or omit collection to span every collection in the tenant